Here's a complete example. I'll use a weather API as a concrete REST wrapper.

---

### Tool Class — `WeatherTools.cs`

```csharp
using ModelContextProtocol.Server;
using System.ComponentModel;
using System.Text.Json;

[McpServerToolType]
public class WeatherTools(HttpClient httpClient, ILogger<WeatherTools> logger)
{
    private const string BaseUrl = "https://api.open-meteo.com/v1";

    [McpServerTool, Description("Get the current weather for a location by latitude and longitude.")]
    public async Task<string> GetCurrentWeather(
        [Description("Latitude of the location (e.g. 47.6)")] double latitude,
        [Description("Longitude of the location (e.g. -122.3)")] double longitude,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        logger.LogInformation("Fetching weather for ({Lat}, {Lon})", latitude, longitude);

        var url = $"{BaseUrl}/forecast?latitude={latitude}&longitude={longitude}"
                + "&current=temperature_2m,wind_speed_10m&temperature_unit=fahrenheit";

        var response = await httpClient.GetStringAsync(url, cancellationToken);
        return response;
    }

    [McpServerTool(ReadOnly = true), Description("Look up coordinates for a city name.")]
    public async Task<string> GeolocateCity(
        [Description("City name to look up (e.g. 'Seattle')")] string cityName,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        var url = $"https://geocoding-api.open-meteo.com/v1/search?name={Uri.EscapeDataString(cityName)}&count=1";
        var json = await httpClient.GetStringAsync(url, cancellationToken);
        return json;
    }
}
```

### `Program.cs` — stdio transport

```csharp
using Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Hosting;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Logging;

var builder = Host.CreateApplicationBuilder(args);

// CRITICAL: Log to stderr only — stdout is the JSON-RPC transport
builder.Logging.AddConsole(options =>
    options.LogToStandardErrorThreshold = LogLevel.Trace);

builder.Services.AddHttpClient();  // registers IHttpClientFactory + HttpClient

builder.Services.AddMcpServer(options =>
{
    options.ServerInfo = new() { Name = "WeatherMcpServer", Version = "1.0.0" };
    options.ServerInstructions = "Provides weather data. Use GeolocateCity first, then GetCurrentWeather.";
})
.WithStdioServerTransport()
.WithToolsFromAssembly();          // discovers all [McpServerToolType] classes

await builder.Build().RunAsync();
```

---

### How DI Works for MCP Tools

The SDK has **two injection styles**, both powered by the standard `Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection` container:

| Style | Class type | How services arrive |
|---|---|---|
| **Constructor injection** | Non-static class | Services passed via primary constructor (shown above). The class is instantiated per-call with DI resolution. |
| **Method injection** | Static class | DI services appear as method parameters alongside user-facing params. |

**Key rule:** The SDK automatically distinguishes DI services from tool parameters. Types registered in DI (`HttpClient`, `ILogger<T>`, your own services) are resolved silently and **never appear** in the tool's JSON schema. Only parameters with `[Description]` are exposed to the LLM.

These types are **always injectable** without registration:

- `CancellationToken` — cooperative cancellation
- `IMcpServer` — server instance (send notifications, log)
- `IProgress<ProgressNotificationValue>` — report progress
- `RequestContext<CallToolRequestParams>` — full request context

**Constructor injection** (non-static, shown above) is preferred when tools share state or multiple services. **Method injection** (static class) works for simple, stateless tools:

```csharp
[McpServerToolType]
public static class SimpleTools
{
    [McpServerTool, Description("Ping a URL.")]
    public static async Task<string> Ping(
        [Description("URL to ping")] string url,
        HttpClient httpClient,              // ← injected by DI, hidden from schema
        CancellationToken cancellationToken)
    {
        var resp = await httpClient.GetAsync(url, cancellationToken);
        return $"Status: {(int)resp.StatusCode}";
    }
}
```

To scaffold this as a real project, run:

```bash
dotnet new mcpserver -n WeatherMcpServer
```

Then replace the generated tool class and `Program.cs` with the code above.
